ðŸ§© What .map() actually does

.map() is an array method used to transform each element of an array into a new value.
It creates a new array with the same length as the original one.

ðŸ‘‰ Syntax:

array.map((element, index, array) => {
  // return new value for this element
});

Parameters:

element â†’ the current value being processed.

index â†’ the index (0, 1, 2, â€¦).

array â†’ the entire array itself (rarely used, but available).



---

ðŸ§  Example 1 â€“ basic map

const arr = [2, 3, 4];

const newArr = arr.map((value) => {
  return value * value;
});

console.log(newArr);  // [4, 9, 16]

âœ… Explanation:

For each element in arr,
it returns value * value.

That means new array = [2*2, 3*3, 4*4].



---

ðŸ§  Example 2 â€“ using all parameters (value, index, array)

const arr = [2, 3, 4];

const result = arr.map((value, index, array) => {
  console.log("Value:", value, "Index:", index, "Array:", array);
  return value * 2;
});

console.log(result);

Output:

Value: 2 Index: 0 Array: [2,3,4]
Value: 3 Index: 1 Array: [2,3,4]
Value: 4 Index: 2 Array: [2,3,4]
[4, 6, 8]

ðŸ‘‰ So yes, you can write all three (value, index, array) â€”
but if you donâ€™t need them, you can use only (value).


