  return index * index;
});

console.log(result);

Output:

[0, 1, 4, 9]

âœ… Explanation:

The index doesnâ€™t change in the original array.

Youâ€™re just using it to calculate a new value.

.map() never modifies your original array or its indexes â€”
it only returns a new array of whatever values you return.


So, even if you do return index * index, youâ€™re simply mapping indexes into new numbers.


---

ðŸ§  Example 4 â€“ combine both index and value

